  "prompt": "Is using \"hairs\" instead of \"hair\" grammatically incorrect?",
  "response": "The word \"hair\" is typically used as a mass noun to refer to the collective strands on one's head or body: \"She has long hair.\" In these cases, \"hair\" is treated as singular.\n\nHowever, \"hairs\" is grammatically correct when you wish to emphasize individual strands of hair: \"I found three hairs on my pillow.\" In this context, \"hairs\" is used as a plural form to refer to specific, distinct strands.\n\nSo, whether \"hairs\" is correct depends on the context in which you are using it.",
